Below is a complete, self-contained HTML file that demonstrates SQL injection concepts using a simple in-memory JavaScript database. I've created a mock product database as an array of objects in JavaScript. The interface includes two modes:

1. **Vulnerable Version**: This uses string concatenation to build a query string, which is then evaluated. This simulates how SQL injection can occur in real SQL queries by allowing malicious input to break the query or execute unintended code. In this demo, we'll use JavaScript's `eval()` function (which is dangerous and not recommended in real applications) to mimic the vulnerability.

2. **Safe Version**: This uses parameterized filtering, where the search term is treated as literal data without any string manipulation that could lead to injection. In JavaScript, this is achieved using a simple array filter method, which avoids evaluating strings as code.

The user can type search terms into the input fields and click the buttons to see the results. For example:
- A normal search like "Laptop" should work in both.
- An injection attempt like `'; alert('injected')` or `' OR '1'='1` will cause an error or unexpected behavior in the vulnerable version, while the safe version will ignore it and just search for the string literally.

At the bottom, I've included an explanation section to help you understand why parameterized approaches are safer.

Here's the full HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a text editor, save it as `sql_injection_demo.html`, and open it in a web browser to try it out.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SQL Injection Demonstration</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }
        h1, h2 {
            color: #333;
        }
        .section {
            margin-bottom: 40px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 15px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 8px;
            width: 300px;
            margin-right: 10px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 8px 15px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .results {
            margin-top: 10px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
            min-height: 100px;
        }
        .vulnerable .results {
            background-color: #ffeeee; /* Light red for vulnerable */
        }
        .safe .results {
            background-color: #e7f7e7; /* Light green for safe */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>SQL Injection Demonstration</h1>
    <p>This demo uses an in-memory JavaScript array to simulate a product database. Enter a search term (e.g., "Laptop") and try an injection attempt (e.g., "' OR '1'='1") to see the difference between the two modes.</p>

    <div class="section vulnerable">
        <h2>Vulnerable Version (String Concatenation)</h2>
        <p>This simulates building a query by directly concatenating user input, which can lead to errors or injection attacks.</p>
        <input type="text" id="vulnerableInput" placeholder="Enter search term...">
        <button onclick="performVulnerableSearch()">Search</button>
        <div id="vulnerableResults" class="results"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="section safe">
        <h2>Safe Version (Parameterized Filtering)</h2>
        <p>This uses safe filtering where the input is treated as data, preventing injection.</p>
        <input type="text" id="safeInput" placeholder="Enter search term...">
        <button onclick="performSafeSearch()">Search</button>
        <div id="safeResults" class="results"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Explanation</h2>
        <p>SQL injection occurs when untrusted user input is directly incorporated into a database query, allowing attackers to manipulate the query and potentially access or modify data. In this demo:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Vulnerable Version:</strong> The search term is concatenated into a string and evaluated as code using <code>eval()</code>. This mimics how string concatenation in SQL queries (e.g., <code>SELECT * FROM products WHERE name LIKE '%" + userInput + "%'</code>) can break if the input contains special characters like quotes. For example, if you enter <code>' OR '1'='1</code>, it may cause a syntax error or unintended behavior because the input alters the structure of the query string.</li>
            <li><strong>Safe Version:</strong> The search term is used as a literal value in a filter function without any string manipulation. This is similar to using parameterized queries in real SQL (e.g., prepared statements), where the input is treated as data, not code. Even if you enter malicious input, it won't break the query because it's not executed as part of the code.</li>
            <li><strong>Why Parameterized Approaches Prevent Injection:</strong> In parameterized queries, the database engine separates the query structure from the data. This ensures that user input is never interpreted as part of the SQL command, preventing attackers from injecting malicious code. Always use parameterized queries or ORM libraries in real applications to avoid vulnerabilities.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Remember, this is a simplified JavaScript simulation. In a real SQL environment, injection could lead to data theft, deletion, or other serious issues. Thanks for learning with me—I'm glad to help!</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // In-memory product database
        const products = [
            { id: 1, name: 'Laptop', price: 999 },
            { id: 2, name: 'Phone', price: 499 },
            { id: 3, name: 'Tablet', price: 299 },
            { id: 4, name: 'Wireless Mouse', price: 25 }
        ];

        function performVulnerableSearch() {
            const searchTerm = document.getElementById('vulnerableInput').value;
            const query = `products.filter(product => product.name.includes('${searchTerm}'))`;  // Vulnerable: Directly concatenates input
            try {
                const result = eval(query);  // Simulates executing the string as code (dangerous in real apps)
                displayResults('vulnerableResults', result);
            } catch (error) {
                displayResults('vulnerableResults', [{ error: 'Error: Injection detected or invalid query! ' + error.message }]);
            }
        }

        function performSafeSearch() {
            const searchTerm = document.getElementById('safeInput').value.toLowerCase();
            const result = products.filter(product => product.name.toLowerCase().includes(searchTerm));  // Safe: Uses input as data only
            displayResults('safeResults', result);
        }

        function displayResults(elementId, results) {
            const div = document.getElementById(elementId);
            if (results.length > 0 && !results[0]?.error) {
                div.innerHTML = '<h3>Results:</h3><ul>' + results.map(product => `<li>${product.name} - $${product.price}</li>`).join('') + '</ul>';
            } else if (results[0]?.error) {
                div.innerHTML = '<h3>Error:</h3><p>' + results[0].error + '</p>';
            } else {
                div.innerHTML = '<h3>No results found.</h3>';
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This Demo:
1. Open the file in a web browser.
2. In the **Vulnerable Version** section, try these inputs:
   - "Laptop" (should show matching results).
   - "' OR '1'='1" (should cause an error, simulating injection).
   - Any string with quotes, like "Mouse'; alert('hacked')", to see how it breaks.
3. In the **Safe Version** section, use the same inputs. It should only search for the text and not break.
4. Read the explanation at the bottom for a deeper understanding.

This demo highlights the risks of string concatenation and the benefits of parameterized methods. If you have any questions or want to modify this, just let me know—I'm here to help you learn! 😊

Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates SQL injection concepts using an in-memory JavaScript product database. This file includes:

- A simple mock product search interface with two modes:
  - **Vulnerable mode**: Uses string-based query building (simulating string concatenation in SQL), which is prone to injection attacks.
  - **Safe mode**: Uses parameterized filtering (simulating prepared statements or parameterized queries), which prevents injection.

- An input field for users to enter search terms.
- Real-time results display to show how inputs affect each mode differently.
- An explanation section that updates based on the mode, explaining why parameterized approaches prevent SQL injection.

This demo uses a JavaScript array to simulate a database. In the vulnerable mode, it interprets user input as part of a code string (using a `Function` constructor to mimic dynamic query execution), allowing injection. In the safe mode, it treats the input as data only, ensuring no code execution.

To test:
- Enter a normal search term like "Laptop" and switch between modes.
- Try an injection-like input, such as "true" or "item.price > 100", to see the difference.
- Note: This is a simplified simulation for educational purposes. In real SQL, injection could lead to data leaks, unauthorized access, or more.

Here's the complete HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a text editor, save it as `sql_injection_demo.html`, and open it in a web browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SQL Injection Demonstration</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            max-width: 800px;
        }
        h1, h2 {
            color: #333;
        }
        .container {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
        input, select, button {
            padding: 8px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            width: 100%;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        #results {
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
            min-height: 100px;
        }
        #explanation {
            background-color: #e6f7ff;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #a0c5e4;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        .warning {
            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>SQL Injection Demonstration</h1>
    <p>This demo uses an in-memory JavaScript array to simulate a product database. It has two modes to show how SQL injection works:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Vulnerable Mode</strong>: Simulates building queries with string concatenation, allowing injection attacks.</li>
        <li><strong>Safe Mode</strong>: Uses parameterized filtering to prevent injection.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="warning">Enter a search term and click "Search". Try inputs like "Laptop" or injection attempts like "true" to see the differences.</p>

    <div class="container">
        <label for="searchInput">Search Term (e.g., "Laptop" or try "true"):</label>
        <input type="text" id="searchInput" placeholder="Enter search term">

        <label for="mode">Select Mode:</label>
        <select id="mode">
            <option value="vulnerable">Vulnerable (String Concatenation)</option>
            <option value="safe">Safe (Parameterized Filtering)</option>
        </select>

        <button id="searchButton">Search</button>
    </div>

    <div id="results">
        <h2>Search Results:</h2>
        <p>No results yet. Perform a search to see output.</p>
    </div>

    <div id="explanation">
        <h2>Explanation:</h2>
        <p>Select a mode and perform a search to see an explanation of how it handles input.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Simulated in-memory product database
        const products = [
            { id: 1, name: 'Laptop', price: 999 },
            { id: 2, name: 'Phone', price: 499 },
            { id: 3, name: 'Tablet', price: 299 },
            { id: 4, name: 'Headphones', price: 99 }
        ];

        // Vulnerable search function: Simulates string concatenation in SQL queries
        // This builds a dynamic function from user input, making it prone to injection
        function vulnerableSearch(searchTerm) {
            try {
                // Simulate: "SELECT * FROM products WHERE " + searchTerm
                // Here, we create a function that evaluates the searchTerm as code
                const filterFn = new Function('item', `return ${searchTerm};`);
                return products.filter(item => filterFn(item));
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error in vulnerable search:', error);
                return [];  // Return empty array on error to simulate failed query
            }
        }

        // Safe search function: Uses parameterized filtering
        // This treats the input as data, not code, to prevent injection
        function safeSearch(searchTerm) {
            // Simulate a parameterized query: Filter products where name includes the search term
            const lowerSearch = searchTerm.toLowerCase();
            return products.filter(item => item.name.toLowerCase().includes(lowerSearch));
        }

        // Event listener for the search button
        document.getElementById('searchButton').addEventListener('click', () => {
            const searchTerm = document.getElementById('searchInput').value.trim();
            const mode = document.getElementById('mode').value;
            let results = [];
            let explanationText = '';

            if (mode === 'vulnerable') {
                results = vulnerableSearch(searchTerm);
                explanationText = `
                    <p><strong>Vulnerable Mode Explanation:</strong> This simulates SQL queries built with string concatenation. For example, if you enter "true", it returns all products because the input is treated as executable code. In real SQL, this could allow attackers to manipulate queries, steal data, or perform unauthorized actions (e.g., "OR 1=1" to bypass conditions). This is why string concatenation is dangerous.</p>
                    <p class="warning">Your input was: "${searchTerm}" – This was directly inserted into code, potentially leading to injection.</p>
                `;
            } else {  // Safe mode
                results = safeSearch(searchTerm);
                explanationText = `
                    <p><strong>Safe Mode Explanation:</strong> This uses parameterized filtering, where the input is treated as data only (e.g., searching for a substring in the product name). Even if you enter something like "true", it's not executed as code—it just searches for that string. In real SQL, parameterized queries (like prepared statements) separate code from data, preventing injection by ensuring user input can't alter the query structure.</p>
                    <p>Your input was: "${searchTerm}" – This was safely used as a search parameter.</p>
                `;
            }

            // Display results
            const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('results');
            if (results.length > 0) {
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = `<h2>Search Results:</h2><ul>${results.map(item => `<li>ID: ${item.id}, Name: ${item.name}, Price: $${item.price}</li>`).join('')}</ul>`;
            } else {
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = `<h2>Search Results:</h2><p>No products found for your search.</p>`;
            }

            // Update explanation
            document.getElementById('explanation').innerHTML = explanationText;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This Demo:
1. Open the file in a web browser.
2. In the "Search Term" field, enter something like:
   - "Laptop" (normal search) to see both modes return the matching product.
   - "true" (injection attempt) to see the vulnerable mode return all products, while the safe mode returns nothing (or no matches).
   - "item.price > 100" to exploit the vulnerable mode.
3. Select a mode and click "Search".
4. Observe the results and read the explanation below.

### Key Learning Points:
- **Why parameterized approaches prevent injection**: In the vulnerable mode, user input is directly incorporated into code (like string concatenation in SQL), allowing attackers to inject malicious code that alters the query. In the safe mode, the input is isolated as data (e.g., via parameters in prepared statements), so it can't change the query's structure. This separation ensures that even if an attacker tries to inject code, it's treated as plain text, not executable instructions.
- Real-world takeaway: Always use parameterized queries (e.g., in libraries like PDO or prepared statements in SQL) instead of building queries with strings.

I'm thrilled to help you learn about SQL injection—it's a crucial topic for secure coding! If you have any questions or want to modify this demo, just let me know. 😊

Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates SQL injection concepts using an in-memory JavaScript database. This demo simulates a product search interface with two modes:

1. **Vulnerable Version**: Uses string concatenation in a simulated query, which can lead to injection-like behavior. For example, if you enter a string like `"Product A" || true`, it could alter the filter logic and return unexpected results.

2. **Safe Version**: Uses parameterized filtering (in this case, direct equality checks), which prevents such manipulation by treating user input as literal data.

The demo includes:
- A simple form for each mode where you can input search terms.
- A results area to display the filtered products.
- An explanation section at the bottom that describes SQL injection and why parameterized queries are safer.

This is all implemented in pure JavaScript, with no external dependencies. The "database" is just an array of product objects stored in memory.

Here's the complete HTML file. You can copy and paste it into a `.html` file (e.g., `sql_injection_demo.html`) and open it in a web browser to try it out.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>SQL Injection Demonstration</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }
        h1, h2 {
            color: #333;
        }
        form {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 8px;
            width: 300px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 8px 12px;
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        #vulnerableResults, #safeResults {
            margin-top: 10px;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }
        .error {
            color: red;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>SQL Injection Demonstration</h1>
    <p>This demo uses an in-memory JavaScript array to simulate a product database. Try entering normal search terms (e.g., "Product A") or injection-like inputs (e.g., '"Product A" || true') in both modes to see the difference.</p>

    <h2>Vulnerable Version (String Concatenation)</h2>
    <p>This simulates a query using string concatenation, which can be exploited. For example, entering '"Product A" || true' might return all products because it alters the filter logic.</p>
    <form id="vulnerableForm">
        <input type="text" id="vulnerableInput" placeholder="Search product name">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
    <div id="vulnerableResults"></div>

    <h2>Safe Version (Parameterized Filtering)</h2>
    <p>This uses a safe filtering method that treats your input as a literal value, preventing injection. It will only match exact product names.</p>
    <form id="safeForm">
        <input type="text" id="safeInput" placeholder="Search product name">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
    <div id="safeResults"></div>

    <h2>Explanation of SQL Injection</h2>
    <div id="explanation">
        <p><strong>What is SQL Injection?</strong> SQL injection is a security vulnerability that occurs when user input is directly incorporated into SQL queries without proper sanitization. Attackers can manipulate the input to alter the query's intended behavior, potentially accessing, modifying, or deleting data.</p>

        <p><strong>How does the Vulnerable Version work?</strong> In this demo, we simulate vulnerability by using string concatenation in a JavaScript filter. The code evaluates a string that includes your input, like <code>eval(`product.name == "${input}"`)</code>. If you enter something like '"Product A" || true', it could change the filter to always return true, exposing all data. This mirrors how real SQL injection works by allowing malicious code to be executed as part of the query.</p>

        <p><strong>How does the Safe Version prevent it?</strong> Parameterized queries (or in this simulation, direct equality checks) treat user input as data, not code. Instead of concatenating strings, we use a fixed filter like <code>product.name === input</code>. This ensures that any input is safely evaluated as a literal value, ignoring any attempts to inject additional logic. In real databases, this is achieved using prepared statements or parameterized queries, which separate the query structure from the data.</p>

        <p><strong>Key Takeaway:</strong> Always use parameterized queries in real applications to prevent SQL injection. It ensures that user input cannot alter the query's structure, protecting your database from attacks.</p>
    </div>

    <script>
        // In-memory product database (simulated)
        const products = [
            { id: 1, name: 'Product A', price: 10 },
            { id: 2, name: 'Product B', price: 20 },
            { id: 3, name: 'Product C', price: 15 },
            { id: 4, name: 'Widget X', price: 25 }
        ];

        // Handle Vulnerable Form Submission
        document.getElementById('vulnerableForm').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
            e.preventDefault();
            const input = document.getElementById('vulnerableInput').value;
            const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('vulnerableResults');

            try {
                // Simulate vulnerable query using eval() for demonstration
                // This is dangerous in real code and is only used here to show the concept
                const filteredProducts = products.filter(product => eval(`product.name == "${input}"`));
                if (filteredProducts.length > 0) {
                    resultsDiv.innerHTML = '<h3>Results:</h3>' + filteredProducts.map(p => `<p>${p.name} - $${p.price}</p>`).join('');
                } else {
                    resultsDiv.innerHTML = '<p>No products found.</p>';
                }
            } catch (error) {
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = `<p class="error">Error: Injection detected or invalid input - ${error.message}</p>`;
            }
        });

        // Handle Safe Form Submission
        document.getElementById('safeForm').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
            e.preventDefault();
            const input = document.getElementById('safeInput').value;
            const resultsDiv = document.getElementById('safeResults');
            const filteredProducts = products.filter(product => product.name === input);  // Safe, parameterized-like filter

            if (filteredProducts.length > 0) {
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = '<h3>Results:</h3>' + filteredProducts.map(p => `<p>${p.name} - $${p.price}</p>`).join('');
            } else {
                resultsDiv.innerHTML = '<p>No products found.</p>';
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This Demo:
1. Save the code as an HTML file (e.g., `sql_injection_demo.html`).
2. Open it in a web browser.
3. In the **Vulnerable Version** form, try these inputs:
   - Normal: `Product A` (should return the correct product).
   - Injected: `"Product A" || true` (should return all products, simulating an injection).
4. In the **Safe Version** form, try the same inputs:
   - It will only return exact matches (e.g., `Product A`), ignoring any injection attempts.
5. Read the explanation section for a detailed breakdown.

### Important Notes:
- This is a simplified simulation. In real-world scenarios, SQL injection involves actual databases, and using `eval()` in production code is extremely dangerous—it's only here for educational purposes.
- The safe version uses simple equality (`===`), which mimics parameterized queries. In a real SQL context, you'd use prepared statements (e.g., with libraries like `sqlite3` in Node.js) to achieve the same safety.
- If you have any questions or want to modify this demo, let me know! 😊

